@node "Introduction" "introduction"

@{b}Introduction@{ub}
------------

MultiHelp is a program which provides you with online help for almost any
program that you may be using from workbench. Most programs these days offer you
the ability to press a hotkey or select an option from a menu which will bring
up the programs online help, however there is a lot of software around
which doesn't provide you with this ability. In comes MultiHelp.

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "requirements"

@{b}Minimum Requirements@{ub}
--------------------

lowlevel.library - Version 40+
reqtools.library - Version 38+ (by Nico Francois)

MultiHelp has been tested on the following machines.

A4000T (040@25Mhz)
2MB CHIP + 16MB FAST
CV64/3d 4MB Gfx Card
Tandem Controller
GVP Serial/Parallel/MIDI Card
386SX25Mhz BridgeBoard
2xMitsumi CDROM, 12xIDE CDROM
OS 3.0

A3000 (030@25Mhz)
1MB CHIP + 16MB FAST
Picasso II 2MB Gfx Card
GVP SCSI Card
4xSCSI CDROM
OS 3.1

A1200 (030@50Mhz)
2MB CHIP + 8MB FAST
Blizzard MkIV Accelerator.

A1200 (040@25Mhz/PPC 603e@200Mhz)
2MB CHIP + 16MB FAST
24x SCSI
ZIP Drive
OS3.0


MultiHelp has *not* been tested on WB 2.0+ however I see no reason why it
shouldn't work.

Programs to view ASCII, AmigaGuide and HTML are recommended. :)

@endnode

@node "Usage" "usage"

@{b}Usage.@{ub}
------

MultiHelp can be started from Workbench, the CLI or automatically from
WBStartup.

@{b}Starting from Workbench.@{ub}
------------------------

Just set the tooltypes and double-click on its icon! :)

MultiHelps Tooltypes.
---------------------

   @{b}GUIDE@{ub} : Path and filename of program to view AmigaGuides.
   Default: SYS:UTILITIES/MULTIVIEW

   @{b}HTML@{ub}  : Path and filename of program to view HTML.
   Default: SYS:UTILITIES/MULTIVIEW

   @{b}TXT@{ub}   : Path and filename of program to view ASCII.
   Default: SYS:UTILITIES/MULTIVIEW

   @{b}DIR@{ub}   : The default directory to open Multihelp in.
   Default: HELP:

   @{b}HOTKEY@{ub}: The Hotkey to bring up online HELP. (F1 to F10 and HELP)
   Default: HELP

   @{b}QUIT@{ub}  : The Hotkey to quit Multihelp. (F1 to F10 and HELP)
   Default: F10


If any of the tooltypes are missing or commented out then MultiHelp will use the
default options.


Starting from CLI.
------------------

If MultiHelp is started from the CLI then the tooltypes are ignored and the
default options are used.

Starting from WBStartup
-----------------------

Behaves the same way as if the program was started from Workbench however you
should add the following as the first tooltype to stop Workbench waiting for
the program to return.

DONOTWAIT


How to use Multihelp.
---------------------

To use MultiHelp effectively it is recommended that you copy the documents of
your preferred programs to one main directory. An ideal solution is to copy
them to the assignment HELP: as many programs use this directory anyway. Once
MultiHelp is running, press the HOTKEY at any time on any screen or window and
MultiHelp will open a file requestor in your default document directory. There
you may select the document you are interested in and depending on it's type,
MultiHelp will launch the appropriate viewer. To QUIT MultiHelp simply press
it's QUIT hotkey at any time.


@endnode

